Hi Nathan,

You can use the &quot;failonerror&quot; and &quot;resultproperty&quot; attributes of the 
&lt;java&gt; task to stop the build if the junit.textui.TestRunner returns 
non-zero (indicating test failure or error).

Having said that, I would personally recommend using the &lt;junit&gt; task 
that is provided in the Ant optional tasks package, because it gives you 
much better control of how your tests are executed and nicer reporting.

Regards,
-Brendan
http://www.thecortex.net


